1. An impeachment inquiry is not an impeachment. An impeachment inquiry *may* lead to an impeachment but does not necessarily have to.

2. An impeachment can only take place once the entire House of Representatives votes, with a required majority, to impeach the President. A President who has been impeached remains in power and has all the duties and responsibilities that he had before the impeachment vote. An impeachment is similar to an indictment against an accused. A person who is indicted simply goes to trial, he is *not* presumed guilty of anything.

3. If an impeachment vote takes place by the House, the Senate must take up the matter. It cannot simply do nothing. Doing nothing means the impeachment continues to linger out there and the President's detractors will say that the Senate was afraid to take up the matter. What the Senate can and should do in that case is take up the indictment and dismiss it for lack of evidence or lack of basis sufficient for a trial.

What is Section 230?

The Communications Decency Act is an obscure law passed by Congress in 1996 that has profoundly shaped today’s internet. 

A provision of that law is what’s so hotly contested. Section 230 was intended to protect free expression on the internet by shielding internet companies from liability for much of the content their users post on their platforms and granting companies legal immunity for good faith efforts to remove content. 

That provision helped fuel the rise of the modern internet. Companies like Facebook, Twitter and Google-owned YouTube say they could not exist in their current form without its protections.

There are exceptions to the law, such as federal crimes and intellectual property claims. Also in 2018, lawmakers chipped away at Section 230 protections by passing a law that makes it easier to sue internet platforms that knowingly aid sex trafficking.

One of my favorite political commentators, Walter Williams, died today at the age of 84. I discovered his weekly newspaper articles in the early 1990s when I first became deeply interested in politics. I always loved that he looked beyond conventional wisdom and dug deeply into whatever topic he was covering, with his combination of common sense, expertise of economics and history, and intellectual humor. And he was one of the best at explaining complicated issues in a way that the common man could grasp. I attended a speech of his in Louisville, Kentucky on February 28, 1995 and met him briefly after the speech.

One of my favorite works that he ever did is this documentary, which was released all the way back in 1984, but is as relevant today as ever. It simply but brilliantly explains how well intentioned government attempts to alleviate poverty can have very much the opposite effect.

One of my favorite political commentators, Walter Williams, died today at the age of 84. I discovered his weekly newspaper articles in the early 1990s when I first became deeply interested in politics. I always loved that he looked beyond conventional wisdom and dug deeply into whatever topic he was covering, with his combination of common sense, expertise of economics and history, and intellectual humor. And he was one of the best at explaining complicated issues in a way that the common man could grasp. I attended a speech of his in Louisville, Kentucky on February 28, 1995 and met him briefly after the speech.

One of my favorite works that he ever did is this documentary, which was released all the way back in 1984, but is as relevant today as ever. It simply but brilliantly explains how well intentioned government attempts to alleviate poverty can have very much the opposite effect.
